# PR Lifecycle Automation

Use the repo-local PR lifecycle skills as the default path for PR submission, merge readiness, and post-merge cleanup.

## Primary Triggers

- When the user asks to stack a PR, submit work, create or open a PR, push for review, babysit CI, or prep a branch for merge, first read and follow `.cursor/skills/prep-for-merge/SKILL.md`.
- When the user asks to merge a PR, check merge readiness, auto-merge a reviewed PR, or clean up after a merge, first read and follow `.cursor/skills/merge-and-clean/SKILL.md`.
- If the merge already happened and the user wants cleanup only, use the cleanup path from `.cursor/skills/merge-and-clean/SKILL.md` instead of inventing a separate cleanup flow.

## Repo Helpers

- Prefer `pnpm pr:stack` over raw `gt submit`.
- Use `pnpm pr:babysit -- status|pause|resume` to inspect or control the hook-backed PR babysitter.
- Prefer `pnpm pr:validate` over ad hoc lint/build/test command selection.
- Use `gh pr checks` for current status and `gh run view --log-failed` for the failing GitHub Actions step.
- Treat Greptile as a first-class review signal when `greptile.json` is present.

## Auto Continuation

- After `pnpm pr:stack`, `gt submit`, or `gh pr create`, project hooks auto-arm PR babysitting for the current branch PR.
- The project `stop` hook keeps polling GitHub and auto-continues when CI fails, new review feedback lands, or the PR becomes merge-ready.
- Before any final response that should stop that loop, run `pnpm pr:babysit -- pause --reason merge-ready` or `pnpm pr:babysit -- pause --reason needs-user`.

## Approval Boundaries

- Never auto-merge without explicit user confirmation in the current conversation.
- Never auto-clean branches or worktrees without explicit user confirmation in the current conversation.
- Stop and ask when review feedback, CI failures, or merge conflicts are ambiguous.
